content:
Creating an HTML page with a heading, form, text area, and button is quite straightforward. Below is a simple example of how you can structure your HTML code to achieve this:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Simple HTML Form</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
        }
        form {
            max-width: 400px;
            margin: auto;
            padding: 20px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        textarea {
            width: 100%;
            height: 100px;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 15px;
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #45a049;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <h1>Contact Us</h1>
    <form action="/submit" method="post">
        <div>
            <label for="message">Your Message:</label><br>
            <textarea id="message" name="message" placeholder="Write your message here..."></textarea>
        </div>
        <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:

1. **HTML Structure:**
   - The `<!DOCTYPE html>` declaration defines the document type and version of HTML.
   - The `<html>` element is the root element of an HTML page.
   - The `<head>` element contains meta-information about the document, like character set and title.
   - The `<body>` element contains the content of the HTML page.

2. **Styling:**
   - Basic CSS is added within the `<style>` tag to style the form and its elements like text area and button.

3. **Form Elements:**
   - The `<form>` tag defines a form to collect user input.
   - The `<textarea>` element is used to create a multi-line text input.
   - The `<button>` element is used to create a clickable button to submit the form.

4. **Form Attributes:**
   - The `action` attribute specifies where to send the form data when it's submitted.
   - The `method` attribute specifies the HTTP method to use when sending form data.

Feel free to customize the styles and form elements as per your needs!
